The '''New York Farm Winery Act of 1976''' is a law that allows grape growers in [[New York (state)|New York]] to establish [[winery|wineries]] and sell directly to the public, subject to a maximum of {{convert|50000|gal|L}} annually.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Wine Country|url=http://www.lakeeriewinecountry.org/about-wine-country/|publisher=Lake Erie Wine Country|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref>
In the early 1970s, John Miller, of Benmarl Winery, and [[John S. Dyson|John Dyson]], commissioner of agriculture, put together a plan to help revitalize the [[New York wine]] industry, which was foundering at the time. Governor [[Hugh Carey]] signed the plan into law in 1976.<ref name=WinesNY>{{cite web|title=Mark Miller: Farm Winery Act of 1976|url=http://www.winesny.com/NewYorkWines/Articles/Hudson-Valley-Wines-09/Hudson-Valley-Wines-Mark-Miller.aspx|publisher=WinesNY.com|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> The law allowed small grower-producers to sell directly to consumers, as well as reducing certain fees and providing tax and marketing advantages. Originally, the law required farm wineries to sell only estate-grown wines, but it was amended in 1978 to allow the use of any New York-grown grapes in wine sold at a farm winery.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}
